Data analysis for the Multi-country PROMOTE HIV Antiretroviral Treatment Observational Cohort in Sub-Saharan Africa¶

Please note: This notebook uses public access data. Please make sure you have access to the study/data from the relevant data common(s)

Data Source:

  • eLwazi Data Commons
  • Harvard Dataverse
  • Related study publication: https://journals.plos.org/plosone/article?id=10.1371/journal.pone.0208805

Fan Wang
February 27 2023

The PROMOTE study aims to measure long-term antiretroviral treatment (ART) safety and adherence; compare HIV disease progression; assess subsequent adverse pregnancy outcomes; evaluate effect of ART exposure on growth and development in HIV-exposed uninfected children; and assess long-term survival of mothers and children. This report primarily describes cohort characteristics at baseline to better understand long-term outcomes.

This notebook showcases the ability to do exploratory analysis within the eLwazi Data Commons. The analysis is not intended to constitute advice nor is it to be used as a substitute for decision making from a professional.

Data description¶

1. Study design¶

A population-based birth cohort established in 2012 in a peri-urban community outside Cape Town, South Africa, has been described in detail. The population is of low socio-economic status; unemployment and maternal HIV infection are common. Pregnant women (20–28 weeks’ gestation) were recruited and followed through pregnancy and delivery; mother-child pairs were followed through early childhood. For this study, follow-up through the first 2 years of life is included.

2. Import packages¶

We’ll first import all the packages that we need for this notebook:

  • numpy is the fundamental package for scientific computing in python.
  • pandas is what we’ll use to manipulate our data.
  • matplotlib and seaborn are plotting libraries.
  • tableone is a package for creating summary statistics for a patient population.

3. Data description¶

Demographic characteristics:¶

  • ParticipantID: Participant ID.
  • site: Site.
  • AGE: Age.
  • bmi: Body mass index.

Maternal baseline sociodemographic characteristics:¶

  • MARITAL_STATUS: Marital status (No regular partner, separated, primary regular partner, widowed, married, unknown, divorced).
  • TELL_PARTNER_HIV_STAT: Did you tell partner your HIV status.
  • TEST_PARTNER_HIV_STAT: Know if partner tested for HIV.

Maternal baseline antiretroviral treatment information:¶

  • CD4_COUNT: CD4 count.
  • WHO_CLINICAL_CLASSIFICATION: WHO clinical classification (1,2,3,4, unknown).
  • RECEIVED_TB_TREATMENT: Received TB the last 3 months.
  • TAKING_ARV_TREATMENT: Currently taking ARV treatment.
  • option: Regimen type (EFV based, Lpv/r, ATV/r, RTV based, other, unknown).
  • viral_load: Viral load (<200 cp/ml, >1000 cp/ml, 200-399 cp/ml, 400-1000 cp/ml, Undetectable, unknown).

Maternal reproductive history :¶

  • SEXUAL_INTERCOURSE_LAST3MONTHS: Did you have sex in the last 3 months.
  • OFTEN_USE_CONDOMS: How often did you use condoms (always, never, sometimes, unknown).
  • USE_FAMILY_PLANNING: Did you use family planning methods.
  • TOTAL_NUMBER_PREGNANCIES: Total number of pregnancies.
  • CURRENTLY_BREASTFEEDING: Are you currently breastfeeding.
  • NUMBER_CHIDREN_CHOICE: Children would have liked to have-life.
  • LIKE_ANOTHER_CHILD: Would you like to have another child.
  • MORE_CHILDREN_LIKE_TO_HAVE: More children would like to have.
  • WANT_BECOME_PREGNANT: Did you want become pregnant at time.
  • newpreg: New pregnancy.
  • PREGNANCY_OUTCOME: Indicate pregnancy outcome (Abortion/miscarriage <20 weeks, Congential anomalies, Live birth, Low birth weight <2500g, Preterm delivery <37 weeks, Stillbirth/intrauterine fetal death >20 weeks, unknown).
  • bmi: Body mass index.

Exposure:¶

  • contra: Contraceptive (Condoms; Hysterectomy; Implant; Injectable; IUCD; Oral; Tubal ligation; unkown; Withdrawal, Herbs, emergency pill, vasectomy).
  • ELECTRICITY: Electricity in the premises.
  • TAP_WATER: Tap water in the premises.
  • TRAVEL_TIME_TO_CLINIC: Travel time from home to clinic (greater than 2 hours, 1-2 hours, less than 30 minutes, 30-60 minutes, unknown).

Diagnosis:¶

  • FEVER: Fever for more than 2 weeks.
  • COUGH: Cough for more than 2 weeks.
  • LOST_WEIGHT: Lost weightin the last month.
  • NIGHT_SWEATS: Had night sweats.

Data analysis¶

1. PROMOTE enrollment by research site¶

Overall, 1987 mothers were enrolled in PROMOTE from the PROMISE study (Reproduced Table 1 of the related publication). The overall mean age of the women was 31.4 years. The number of new pregnancies in PROMOTE to the time of this analysis and the outcomes of these pregnancies are also shown in the table below. The overall proportions of new pregnancies at the time of analyses was 14.2%. And large amount of pregnancy outcomes were unknown (93.2%).

2. Maternal baseline sociodemographic characteristics by research site¶

This table reproduced Table 3 in the publication. It shows maternal sociodemographic characteristics by site. In particular, there were substantial and statistically significant differences among countries by marital status, socioeconomic status (indicated by availability of electricity and water in the living premises), and travel time to the study clinic. For example, most women (75% or more) reported being married in Malawi (site Blantyre and Lilongwe) and Zimbabwe (site Harare, Seke North and St. Mary's) compared to very low rates in South Africa (4.4% in Durban and 15% in Soweto), and 43.5% in Uganda (site Kampala). Although overall, 30.4% of the women reported 1 hour or more of travel time to access the specific study clinic, there was a wide variability– 58.0% in Uganda (site Kampala), 36.6%-39.9% in Malawi (site Blantyre and Lilongwe), and much less in Zimbabwe (site Harare, Seke North and St. Mary's) and South Africa (site Durban and Soweto). Table 3 also shows maternal nutritional status based on body mass index (BMI) assessment (kg/m2). The overall frequency of being underweight (BMI <18.5) was 4.1%; the sites in Blantyre, Malawi and Seke North, Zimbabwe showed highest frequencies (9.0% and 6.1%, respectively).

3. Visualize the relation between Age and body mass index (BMI)¶

The scatter plot is an effective visual representation of the relationship between age and body mass index (BMI) in women. The plot displays the data points as dots on a two-dimensional graph, with the horizontal axis representing age and the vertical axis representing BMI.

The data indicates that there is a slight positive correlation between age and BMI. This means that as age increases, BMI tends to increase as well. This relationship may be influenced by several factors, such as hormonal changes, lifestyle habits, and metabolism.

Additionally, the plot shows that women with higher age tend to have a larger number of pregnancies. This factor could also be contributing to the observed correlation between age and BMI, as pregnancy and childbirth can impact a woman's weight and body composition.

Overall, this visualization provides valuable insights into the relationship between age and BMI in women, and highlights the potential impact of pregnancy on BMI. It may be useful for healthcare professionals and researchers studying obesity and related health issues in women.

# Create Fig and gridspec
fig = plt.figure(figsize=(11, 8), dpi=80)
grid = plt.GridSpec(4, 4, hspace=0.5, wspace=0.2)

# Define the axes
ax_main = fig.add_subplot(grid[:-1, :-1])
ax_right = fig.add_subplot(grid[:-1, -1], xticklabels=[], yticklabels=[])
ax_bottom = fig.add_subplot(grid[-1, 0:-1], xticklabels=[], yticklabels=[])

# Scatterplot on main ax
scatter = ax_main.scatter(
    "AGE",
    "bmi",
    s=13,
    c=data["TOTAL_NUMBER_PREGNANCIES"].astype("category").cat.codes,
    alpha=1,
    data=data,
    cmap="Reds",
)
legend = ax_main.legend(
    *scatter.legend_elements(prop="colors"),
    loc="upper right",
    title="Total number of\n  pregnancies"
)

# histogram on the right
ax_bottom.hist(
    data.AGE, 50, histtype="stepfilled", orientation="vertical", color="green"
)
ax_bottom.invert_yaxis()

# histogram in the bottom
ax_right.hist(
    data.bmi, 50, histtype="stepfilled", orientation="horizontal", color="green"
)

# Decorations
ax_main.set(
    title="Scatterplot with Histograms \n Age vs. BMI", xlabel="Age", ylabel="BMI"
)
ax_main.title.set_fontsize(20)
for item in (
    [ax_main.xaxis.label, ax_main.yaxis.label]
    + ax_main.get_xticklabels()
    + ax_main.get_yticklabels()
):
    item.set_fontsize(14)

xlabels = ax_main.get_xticks().tolist()
ax_main.set_xticklabels(xlabels)
plt.show()

4. Visualize the relation between viral load classification and CD4 cell count¶

The grouped box plot illustrates the relationship between viral load classification and CD4 cell count in a cohort of women. The x-axis displays the viral load groups, including undetectable, ≤200 copies/mL, 200-399 copies/mL, 400-1000 copies/mL, and >1000 copies/mL. The y-axis represents CD4 cell counts, which is an indicator of immune function.

The data indicates that 85% of the women had an undetectable viral load, while the remaining 15% had detectable viral loads. Among those with detectable viral loads, 77 women had viral loads ≤200 copies/mL, 17 women had viral loads between 200-399 copies/mL, 32 women had viral loads between 400-1000 copies/mL, and 166 women had viral loads >1000 copies/mL.

Each viral load group is further classified by pregnancy outcomes, including live birth, abortion/miscarriage, stillbirth/intrauterine fetal death >20 weeks, preterm delivery <37 weeks, low birth weight <2500g, and congenital anomalies. The box plot displays the distribution of CD4 cell counts for each viral load group and pregnancy outcome.

The box plot shows that women with undetectable viral loads generally had higher CD4 cell counts than those with detectable viral loads. Additionally, women with higher viral loads tended to have lower CD4 cell counts. The box plot also reveals variation in CD4 cell counts across different pregnancy outcomes within each viral load group, highlighting the potential impact of HIV infection on pregnancy outcomes and maternal health.

Overall, this grouped box plot provides a clear and concise summary of the relationship between viral load classification, CD4 cell count, and pregnancy outcomes in women living with HIV. It may be useful for healthcare professionals and researchers studying the impact of HIV on maternal health and pregnancy outcomes.

plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6), dpi=80)
data = data[data.CD4_COUNT != "unknown"]
sns.boxplot(
    x="viral_load",
    y="CD4_COUNT",
    data=data,
    hue="PREGNANCY_OUTCOME",
    order=[
        "Undetectable",
        "<200 cp/ml",
        "200-399 cp/ml",
        "400-1000 cp/ml",
        ">1000 cp/ml",
        "unknown",
    ],
)

# Decoration
plt.title("CD4 cell count by viral load", fontsize=18)
plt.ylabel("CD4 count (cells per uL)")
plt.xlabel("Viral load")
plt.legend(title="Pregnancy outcome")
plt.xticks(rotation=30)
plt.show()

5. Visualize the relation between Regimen option type and CD4 cell count¶

The visualization displays the relationship between different types of antiretroviral therapy (ART) regimen options and CD4 cell count in a large observational cohort of people living with HIV in Sub-Saharan Africa. The ART regimen options included EFV based, Lpv/r, ATV/r, RTV based, other, and unknown.

Each ART regimen group is further classified by WHO clinical classification, including classification 1 (asymptomatic), classification 2 (mild symptoms), classification 3 (advanced symptoms), classification 4 (severe symptoms), and unknown. The x-axis displays the ART regimen options, and the y-axis represents the CD4 cell count.

The visualization shows the distribution of CD4 cell counts across the different ART regimen groups and WHO clinical classifications. The data reveals that the EFV based regimen group had the highest CD4 cell counts on average, while the ATV/r group had the lowest CD4 cell counts on average.

Furthermore, within each ART regimen group, the visualization shows the variation in CD4 cell counts across different WHO clinical classifications. For example, in the EFV based group, individuals with WHO clinical classification 1 tended to have higher CD4 cell counts than those with higher WHO clinical classifications.

Overall, this visualization provides valuable insights into the relationship between ART regimen options, CD4 cell count, and WHO clinical classification in a Sub-Saharan African cohort of people living with HIV. It may be useful for healthcare professionals and researchers studying the effectiveness of different ART regimens and their impact on immune function and clinical outcomes in resource-limited settings.

6. Visualize the relation between Age and Contraceptive practices by Marital status¶

This visualization shows the relationship between age and contraceptive practices among women categorized by marital status. The data is represented in a stacked violin plot, with each contraceptive practice represented by a different color. The x-axis represents the age of the women and the y-axis represents the percentage of women in each marital status category who use each contraceptive method.

The marital status categories are "No regular partner," "Separated," "Primary regular partner," "Widowed," "Married," "Unknown," and "Divorced." For each marital status category, the percentage of women using each contraceptive method is shown. The contraceptive methods include "Condoms," "Hysterectomy," "Implant," "Injectable," "IUCD," "Oral," "Tubal ligation," "Unknown," "Withdrawal," "Herbs," "Emergency pill," and "Vasectomy."

This visualization allows us to see how contraceptive practices vary by age and marital status. For example, we can see that younger women tend to use condoms and oral contraceptives more frequently, while older women tend to use tubal ligation and other permanent methods of contraception. We can also see how contraceptive use varies by marital status, with married women being more likely to use long-term contraceptive methods such as IUCD or tubal ligation, while women with no regular partner are more likely to use condoms or rely on withdrawal.

Overall, this visualization provides insight into how contraceptive practices vary among women based on their age and marital status, which can be useful for public health interventions and family planning programs.

7. Visualize the relation between CD4 cell count and Viral load by Exposure factors¶

These violin plots visualize the relationship between CD4 cell count and Viral load by exposure factors in a HIV antiretroviral treatment observational cohort in Sub-Saharan Africa. The exposure factors are categorized into three groups: electricity, tap water , and travel time to clinic. The violin plots display the distribution of CD4 cell count and Viral load across the exposure groups, with the width of each violin indicating the density of the distribution. The plots allow us to compare the distribution of CD4 cell count and viral load within and across exposure groups, giving us an idea of the impact that each exposure factor has on the health outcomes of the patients in the cohort. The visualization provides valuable insights into the potential risk factors for HIV progression and can inform targeted interventions to improve the health outcomes of HIV-positive individuals in Sub-Saharan Africa.

data["CD4_COUNT"] = data["CD4_COUNT"].astype(int)

g = sns.catplot(

    y="viral_load",
    hue="ELECTRICITY",
    data=data,
    kind="violin",
    bw=0.25,
    cut=0,
    split=True,
    linewidth=0.5,
    order=[
        "Undetectable",
        "<200 cp/ml",
        "200-399 cp/ml",
        "400-1000 cp/ml",
        ">1000 cp/ml",
        "unknown",
    ],
)
plt.xlabel("CD4 cell count (cells per uL)")
plt.ylabel("Viral load")
g.fig.set_figwidth(9)
plt.title("CD4 cell count vs. viral load by access to electricity", fontsize=14)
plt.show()

Summary¶

This notebook replicates the analysis in a recently published study on multi-country HIV antiretroviral treatment observational cohort in Sub-Saharan Africa. In the workspace of eLwazi Data Commons, researchers can apply the commonly used clinical analysis techniques, such as the Kaplan–Meier method, Poisson regression, Cox model, Hazard ratio method, etc. Clinical investigators are encouraged to consider applying these methods for the discovery of immediate and important information to assess HIV treatment and prevention in women using eLwazi Data Commons.

Reference¶

Taha E. Taha, 2018, "Replication Data for: The Multi-country PROMOTE HIV Antiretroviral Treatment Observational Cohort in Sub-Saharan Africa: Objectives, Design, and Baseline Findings", https://doi.org/10.7910/DVN/TYPYXD, Harvard Dataverse, V1.
